 nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Ifor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: (i) relationship name from Old Scandinavian  <i>Ívarr</i>,  <i>Iwar</i>,  <i>Ivar</i> ‘yew-army’. (ii) relationship name, possibly from the Welsh male given name  <i>Ifor</i>; if so, it is not clear that it survives today."],"variants":[{"name":"Ivers","meanings":["Irish: from <b>Ó hÍomhair</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Íomhar</i>’, a Gaelic form of the Old Norse personal name <i>Ívarr</i> (see   Iverson   2), with excrescent English <i>-s</i>. It is occasionally Anglicized as   Howard  . Also a shortened form of <b>Mac Íomhair</b> ‘son of <i>Íomhar</i>’, with excrescent English <i>-s</i>. See   McIver  .","North German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Ivar</i> (see   Iversen  ).","English: variant of <b>Iver</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, a habitational name from Iver (Buckinghamshire) named from Old English <i>ȳfre</i> ‘edge or brow of a hill, tip of a promontory’, or from a minor place called with the same word."]},{"name":"Iver","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Iver (Bucks) named from Old English * <i>ȳfre</i> ‘edge or brow of a hill, tip of a promontory’, or from a minor place named with the same word.","2  Scottish: (i) relationship name, reduced form of Irish and Scottish Gaelic  <b>Mac Íomhair</b>,  see  McIvor  . (ii) relationship name from the Old Scandinavian personal name  <i>Ivar</i>;  see  Ivor  ."]},{"name":"Iverson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Iver, Erik, Hjalmer, Lars, Selmer, Thor, Evald, Gunner, Helmer, Ingman, Jarl, Joneen.","Americanized form of Norwegian, Danish, and North German   Iversen   and of Swedish <b>Ivarsson</b> (see   Ivarson  ), all cognates of 2 below.","English (Kent and London): patronymic from Old Norse <i>Ívarr</i>, <i>Iwar</i>, <i>Ivar</i>, a compound of either <i>ív</i> ‘yew tree, bow’ or <i>Ing</i> (the name of a god) + <i>ar</i> ‘warrior’ or ‘spear’. Alternatively, the name might be a patronymic from the Welsh male personal name <i>Ifor</i>, itself from British Celtic <i>Iūdomāros</i> ‘lord’ + ‘great’, but if so, it is not clear that it survives today."]}]},{"name":"Gwrgan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Meath): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Geargáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Geargán</i>’ or shortened from <b>Mac Geargáin</b> ‘son of <i>Geargán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>garg</i> ‘fierce’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gwrgan ap Ifor was born about 1049, in Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales. She had at least 1 son with Gwrgan ap Ifor."},"et":{"about 1049–":"umbes 1049–Surnud","1030–Male":"1030–Surnud","1075–Male":"1075–Surnud","1049–Female":"1049–Surnud","1049":"1049","about 1049":"umbes 1049","1075":"1075","1030":"1030","Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1049–":"noin 1049–Kuollut","1030–Male":"1030–Kuollut","1075–Male":"1075–Kuollut","1049–Female":"1049–Kuollut","1049":"1049","about 1049":"noin 1049","1075":"1075","1030":"1030","Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1049–":"environ 1049–Décédée","1030–Male":"1030–Décédé","1075–Male":"1075–Décédé","1049–Female":"1049–Décédée","1049":"1049","about 1049":"environ 1049","1075":"1075","1030":"1030","Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gwrgan ap Ifor est née environ 1049, à Montgomery, Montgomerys